Abuja – Ahead of the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) presidential primary scheduled for May 28 and 29, the chairman of the party’s National Convention Organizing Committee, David Mark, has urged PDP faithful across the country to imbibe the spirit of sportsmanship in the conduct of the exercises. Mark, in a statement by his Special Adviser, Paul Mumeh, also warned against politics of acrimony, bitterness or violence, urging party men and women to comply with the rules of the game. Mark, who was the President of the Senate between 2007 and 2015 said, “The party has clear guidelines and rules for the exercises. -Advertisement- Every aspirant should be guided by the processes; the party will not compromise any of the rules.” He counseled delegates to the congresses and conventions to consider the integrity and past accomplishments of aspirants in order to make informed choices of candidates for the elections. “In making your decisions, consider the interest of the people. Politics is a conveyor belt to serve humanity. The greater interest of our people is paramount,” Mark advised. The former President of the Senate cautioned against politics of acrimony, bitterness or violence saying, “see politics like a sporting competition. If you don’t win today, you can win tomorrow.“ He assured of a level playing field for all aspirants, saying, whoever emerged from the open and transparent elections must be the choice of the people.